                <position book_orientation="0" place="tail">
                    <marginalia_text>
                        Meum Principiu[m], et Finis; à duobus pra[e]gnantissimis Titulis; De     
                        Verboru[m] Significatione; et de Regulis Juris. Quo verborum, rerumq[ue]
                        forensium fundamento solidè iacto: co[e]tera omnia, expedita, et prompta.
                        Imò habitis Juris Romani Judicijq[ue], Logici Principiis; facile erit de 
                        omnibus Mundi Legibus judicare.
                    </marginalia_text>
                    <book title="De verborum significatu"/>
                    <book title="De regulis iuris"/>
                    <emphasis method="pen" text="Principiu[m]" type="straight"/>
                    <emphasis method="pen" text="Finis" type="straight"/>
                    <emphasis method="pen" text="Verboru[m]" type="straight"/>
                    <emphasis method="pen" text="de Regulis Juris" type="straight"/>
                    <emphasis method="pen" text="fundamento" type="straight"/>
                    <emphasis method="pen" text="Juris Romani" type="straight"/>
                    <emphasis method="pen" text="Judicijq[ue] Logici" type="straight"/>
                </position>
            </language>
            <translation>
                My foundation and goal come from two pregnant titles: 'De verborum significatione' and
                'De regulis iuris', in which all other things are obtained and produced on a solidly 
                founded basis of words and public matters. With Roman law and its judgements established 
                at root by the principles of logic, it will be easy to judge the laws of the whole world.
            </translation>
        </marginalia>
        
